#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld.L10_ExtIntro
msgid "You proved your first set equality using §0! The structure was:\n"
"\n"
"§1\n"
"\n"
"**Why §2 works**: Since §3, two sets are equal when\n"
"they are equal as functions. The §4 tactic applies **function\n"
"extensionality**: two functions are equal when they agree on all inputs.\n"
"For sets, \"agreeing on all inputs\" means having the same membership\n"
"predicate — which is exactly §5. So set\n"
"extensionality is not an extra axiom — it IS function extensionality\n"
"applied to predicates.\n"
"\n"
"In ordinary math, this proof would read: \"We show the sets are equal\n"
"by double inclusion. If §6 and §7, then certainly §8.\n"
"Conversely, if §9, then also §10 (since §11), so\n"
"§12.\"\n"
"\n"
"**The §13 (focus dot)**: After §14 splits a goal into two\n"
"subgoals, §15 focuses on one at a time. This keeps your proof\n"
"organized — you handle one case completely before moving to the next.\n"
"You will use §16 in nearly every proof that involves §17.\n"
"\n"
"**Dot projections on §18**: If §19, then §20 and\n"
"§21. This is the quickest way to extract one component of a\n"
"conjunction. The same §22/§23 pattern works on §24 (biconditionals)\n"
"too — you will use it later to extract the forward and backward\n"
"implications.\n"
"\n"
"**Destructuring §25**: When a hypothesis is a conjunction §26,\n"
"you can write §27 to introduce and split it in one step,\n"
"instead of §28 followed by §29. This\n"
"shorthand will be especially useful in the next world when working\n"
"with intersections (§30), which are defined as conjunctions.\n"
"\n"
"**Why §31 works on §32**: The §33 type has exactly one\n"
"constructor, §34, which takes two implications as arguments.\n"
"When you write §35 on a §36 goal, Lean applies §37\n"
"and asks you for the two implications — just as §38 on §39\n"
"applies §40. This is why the same tactic works for both\n"
"conjunctions and biconditionals.\n"
"\n"
"The §41 tactic is the primary tool for set equality proofs in Lean.\n"
"You will use it frequently throughout this course."
msgstr ""

