#: Game.Levels.ImageWorld.L06_ImageMonotonicity
msgid "You proved image monotonicity: §0.\n"
"\n"
"The proof was just two steps:\n"
"1. §1 -- destructure image membership\n"
"2. §2 -- reconstruct with updated membership\n"
"\n"
"**The image proof idiom**: This two-step pattern -- destructure then\n"
"reconstruct -- is the core idiom for image proofs:\n"
"\n"
"§3\n"
"\n"
"You modify what goes in the §4 (here: upgrading §5 via §6),\n"
"but the structure stays the same. You will see this pattern in every\n"
"image proof in this world.\n"
"\n"
"**Anonymous constructors for images**: §7 constructs\n"
"§8 by providing:\n"
"- §9 as the witness\n"
"- §10 for membership\n"
"- §11 for the equation §12\n"
"\n"
"This is the compact way to build image membership. You can also use\n"
"§13 for the same effect.\n"
"\n"
"**The witness transfer pattern**: Notice how the proof works: you\n"
"destructure to get a witness §14, then RE-USE the same witness\n"
"to build membership in §15. The witness transfers between sets\n"
"-- only its membership proof changes (from §16 to\n"
"§17). This pattern recurs throughout Image World: the\n"
"same element serves as witness in both the deconstruction and\n"
"reconstruction. Watch for it in Levels 6, 7, and beyond.\n"
"\n"
"**Does the converse hold?** If §18, must §19? No!\n"
"Consider the constant function §20. Then §21\n"
"for any nonempty §22 and §23, so §24 is trivially true\n"
"regardless of whether §25. Injectivity is needed for the converse\n"
"-- you will explore this in Injective World.\n"
"\n"
"**Why §26 is disabled**: In library code, you would\n"
"write §27 to construct image membership\n"
"in one step. We disable it so you learn the witness construction\n"
"§28 -- understanding HOW image membership is built\n"
"is essential for the proofs ahead.\n"
"\n"
"**Comparison with preimage monotonicity** (Preimage World Level 5):\n"
"preimage monotonicity was §29 -- one step! Image monotonicity\n"
"needs §30 -- the existential witness adds overhead.\n"
"This is the tax of the existential.\n"
"\n"
"The library name is §31."
msgstr ""

