#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld
msgid "# Subset World\n"
"\n"
"In Set World, you learned that sets are predicates and membership is\n"
"predicate evaluation. Now you will learn the two fundamental\n"
"relationships between sets: **subset** (§0) and **equality** (§1).\n"
"\n"
"A **subset** proof §2 means: for every element, if it is in §3\n"
"then it is in §4. The proof shape is always §5 — fix an\n"
"element, assume it is in the smaller set, then show it is in the\n"
"larger set.\n"
"\n"
"A **set equality** proof §6 means: the two sets have exactly the\n"
"same elements. There are two routes:\n"
"- **Extensionality** (§7): prove §8 directly\n"
"- **Double containment** (§9): prove §10 and\n"
"  §11 separately\n"
"\n"
"By the end of this world, you will:\n"
"- Prove subset relations with the §12 pattern\n"
"- Handle the boundary cases §13 and §14\n"
"- Use subset hypotheses as functions\n"
"- Disprove false subset claims by contradiction\n"
"- Chain subset proofs transitively\n"
"- Prove set equality via §15 (extensionality)\n"
"- Prove set equality via §16 (double containment)\n"
"- Prove set non-equality by finding a contradictory witness\n"
"- Prove proper subset (§17) by combining §18 and §19\n"
"- Use §20 to unwrap set notation on hypotheses\n"
"\n"
"You will also gain a new tactic (§21) and a new proof strategy\n"
"(double containment) that you will use throughout the rest of this\n"
"course.\n"
"\n"
"**New tools in this world**:\n"
"- §22 — unwrap a hypothesis to a definitionally equal form\n"
"- §23 — reduce set equality to element-wise membership\n"
"- §24 — derive equality from mutual subsets"
msgstr ""

