#: Game.Levels.SetOpsWorld.L12_PushNeg
msgid "# The push_neg Tactic\n"
"\n"
"When working with complements, you often encounter negated\n"
"propositions: §0, §1, §2, etc.\n"
"You *could* break these apart manually, but there is a faster way.\n"
"\n"
"The §3 tactic pushes negation through logical connectives\n"
"using standard equivalences:\n"
"\n"
"| Before push_neg | After push_neg |\n"
"|---|---|\n"
"| §4 | §5 |\n"
"| §6 | §7 |\n"
"| §8 | §9 |\n"
"| §10 | §11 |\n"
"\n"
"You can apply it to a hypothesis with §12, or to the\n"
"goal with just §13.\n"
"\n"
"**Your task**: Prove that the complement of a union is contained in\n"
"the intersection of the complements. This is one direction of\n"
"**De Morgan's law** for sets:\n"
"\n"
"§14\n"
"\n"
"After §15, you will have §16, which is\n"
"definitionally §17. Use §18 to make the negated\n"
"disjunction explicit, then §19 to convert it to\n"
"§20 — which matches the goal.\n"
"\n"
"**Why §21 is needed here**: Lean displays §22\n"
"using set-theoretic complement notation, but §23 needs to see\n"
"the negation explicitly as §24. The tactic\n"
"§25 converts to this definitionally\n"
"equal logical form so §26 can process it. This\n"
"§27 + §28 pattern will recur whenever you work with\n"
"complements of compound sets."
msgstr ""

