#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld.L14_Antisymm
msgid "§0 gives you a one-step path from two ⊆ proofs to\n"
"set equality. Compare the two routes:\n"
"\n"
"| Route | When to use |\n"
"|---|---|\n"
"| §1 | When you need to prove both directions from scratch |\n"
"| §2 | When you already have both ⊆ proofs in hand |\n"
"\n"
"In practice, many set equality proofs start with §3 because you\n"
"rarely have the subset proofs pre-packaged. But §4 is\n"
"valuable when subset facts are available from other lemmas or\n"
"hypotheses.\n"
"\n"
"In ordinary math, this is the well-known principle: \"two sets are\n"
"equal iff each is a subset of the other.\" Every proof of set equality\n"
"by \"double inclusion\" (showing ⊆ in both directions) is implicitly\n"
"using antisymmetry.\n"
"\n"
"A **partial order** is a relation that satisfies three properties:\n"
"1. **Reflexive**: §5 for all §6\n"
"2. **Transitive**: §7 and §8 imply §9\n"
"3. **Antisymmetric**: §10 and §11 imply §12\n"
"\n"
"You have now proved all three for §13 on §14:\n"
"- **Reflexive**: §15 (Level 3)\n"
"- **Transitive**: §16 (Level 8)\n"
"- **Antisymmetric**: §17 (this level)\n"
"\n"
"Together, these make §18 a **partial order** on sets. The partial\n"
"order concept is central to mathematics — you will study it in depth\n"
"in the Orders \\\\& Lattices course.\n"
"\n"
"These two routes — §19 and §20 — are logically *equivalent*.\n"
"You can derive §21 from §22 and §23 from §24. You\n"
"will prove this equivalence yourself in Levels 16 and 17."
msgstr ""

